article.description: Freshman Laura Kurz scored a season-high 20 points Saturday to lead Duke (No. 9 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) to an easy 86-30 win over Pacific.
article.headline: Kurz leads Blue Devils with 20 points
article.linkText: Duke spanks Pacific for 5th straight win
article.story:
DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- The Duke Blue Devils have used the early part of this season to figure out how to win.

Freshman Laura Kurz scored a season-high 20 points Saturday to lead Duke (No. 9 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) to an 86-30 victory over Pacific.

"With each game we've gained confidence that we are a good team," coach Gail Goestenkors said. "We're still learning who we are."

Duke (7-1) won its fifth straight, following up on a two-point victory at Tennessee on Thursday that made the Blue Devils just the seventh visiting team to win at 17-year-old Thompson-Boling Arena.

"At Tennessee, we learned that we can play in any environment with any team in the country and really battle," Goestenkors said. "That was a huge battle, and we gained a lot of confidence from that."

Pacific (2-2) has lost twice to ranked teams, including a Nov. 21 defeat to then-No. 7 Stanford. Tigers coach Craig Jackson thinks his team has gained something from the tough matchups.

"We are a young team of mostly freshmen and sophomores, and the experience of playing Duke is invaluable for them," Jackson said. "We tried to take away their inside game and give them the 3, and I think we did that."

Pacific made just one field goal in the final 11:11 as Duke pulled away. Duke limited Pacific to 21.7 percent shooting (10-for-46) and forced 32 turnovers.

"We came into the game averaging 26 (turnovers) a game, so to have 32 against the way they played wasn't too bad," Jackson said.

Duke led 41-14 after its best first half of shooting this season. The Blue Devils made 17-of-33 shots from the field before halftime and 15-of-33 in the second half. They shot 48.5 percent for the game.

Monique Currie added 18 points, Jessica Foley had 15 and Mistie Williams scored 12 to help the Blue Devils.

"I said from the beginning that it could be anybody's game on any given night," Williams said. "This team has so much talent, it's just going to take a while for everyone to realize what they can bring to the team."

Duke was 10-for-30 from beyond the arc, setting season highs for 3-pointers made and attempted. Duke outrebounded the Tigers 45-32, with Currie and Alison Bales each grabbing eight.

Currie and Jessica Foley each knocked down three 3-pointers, and Kurz made two of her four attempts from long range.

"With each game, I've gotten a little more confident," Kurz said. "I didn't shoot at all at Tennessee, and my goal for this game was to look for my shot. My teammates did a great job getting me the ball and screening for me."

Jessica Brantley and Tina Sanerivi led Pacific with 10 points each.
